Reports 'clone()' methods without the 'final' modifier. Since 'clone()' can be used to instantiate objects without using a constructor, allowing the 'clone()' method to be overridden may result in corrupted objects, and even in security exploits. This may be prevented by making the 'clone()' method or the enclosing class itself 'final'. Example: 'class Main implements Cloneable {
    @Override
    protected Object clone() throws CloneNotSupportedException {
      return super.clone();
    }
  }'

