Reports columns that have identical names but belong to different tables. Example (MySQL): 'CREATE TABLE foo(id INT PRIMARY KEY);
CREATE TABLE bar(id INT PRIMARY KEY);

SELECT foo.id, bar.id FROM foo, bar WHERE id > 0;' The 'id' column appears in 'foo' and 'bar' tables. You need to qualify the column name to make the query correct. 'SELECT foo.id, bar.id FROM foo, bar WHERE foo.id > 0;'

